In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims November 2012 as National Native American Heritage Month. He highlights the significant contributions that Native Americans have made to American society, acknowledging their leadership in various fields. The President also acknowledges the difficult aspects of Native American history, including violence and mistreatment, and expresses his commitment to strengthening the government-to-government relationship with tribal nations and promoting tribal sovereignty. He mentions initiatives such as the Helping Expedite and Advance Responsible Tribal Homeownership (HEARTH) Act and the expansion of educational opportunities for Native American students. The President emphasizes the importance of addressing injustices and creating new avenues of opportunity for American Indians and Alaska Natives. He calls upon all Americans to commemorate the month with appropriate programs and activities and designates November 23, 2012, as Native American Heritage Day.